  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp24.jpg', place: "Ella Rock",rate: 4.6,description: "Famous Mountain Cliff & Hiking Hotspot",category: "Hiking",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best hiked starting early morning around 5:30 AM)",ticketPrice: "Free (Some viewpoints at the summit may charge a small entrance fee of LKR 20 - 50)",fullDescription: "A majestic cliff that towers over the scenic town of Ella, offering one of the most famous hiking experiences in Sri Lanka. The trail takes hikers through operating railway tracks, tea plantations, and dense eucalyptus forests before a steep climb to the peak. At the summit, it rewards adventurers with unparalleled, dramatic panoramic views of the Ella Gap, Little Adam's Peak, and the vast valleys below.",latitude: 6.8650,longitude: 81.0478),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp25.jpg', place: "Gangaramaya Temple",rate: 4.6,description: "Historic Buddhist Temple & Museum",category: "Religious",openingHours: "6:00 AM - 10:00 PM",ticketPrice: "LKR 100 - 200 (Locals) / LKR 500 - 1000 (Foreigners) *Includes entry to Seema Malaka",fullDescription: "One of the most important and iconic Buddhist temples in Colombo, blending Sri Lankan, Thai, Chinese, and Indian architectural styles. Situated near the Beira Lake, it serves as a place of worship, a learning center, and a vast museum housing a priceless collection of Buddha statues, gems, artifacts, and vintage cars gifted by devotees over decades. It is also the central hub for the spectacular annual Navam Perahera festival.",latitude: 6.9167,longitude: 79.8594),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp26.jpg', place: "Gregory Lake",rate: 4.6,description: "Artificial Lake & Recreational Park",category: "Water Sports",openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM",ticketPrice: "LKR 50 - 100 (Locals) / LKR 500 - 1000 (Foreigners) *Activity prices apply separately",fullDescription: "A beautiful, historic artificial lake located in the heart of Nuwara Eliya, constructed under British Governor Sir William Gregory in 1873. Surrounded by lush green hills, it serves as the premier recreational hub in the hill country. Visitors can enjoy a wide array of activities, including swan pedal boat rides, speed boating, jet skiing, horseback riding, pony rides, and cycling along the paved scenic pathways surrounding the lake.",latitude: 6.9632,longitude: 80.7818),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp27.jpg', place: "World's End",rate: 4.7,description: "Breathtaking Mountain Cliff & Viewpoint",category: "Hiking",openingHours: "6:00 AM - 4:00 PM (Best visited between 6:00 AM and 9:00 AM before mist rolls in)",ticketPrice: "Included in Horton Plains National Park ticket (Fees apply per group/vehicle)",fullDescription: "A stunning precipice located within the Horton Plains National Park, featuring a sheer cliff drop of nearly 880 meters (2,854 feet). It is one of the most visited tourist destinations in Sri Lanka, offering an unparalleled panoramic view of the southern plains towards the Indian Ocean on a clear day. The location is reached via a scenic 9.5 km circular walking trail that also passes through the beautiful Baker's Falls.",latitude: 6.7831,longitude: 80.7915),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp28.jpg', place: "Hayes Mountain",rate: 4.6,description: "Misty Tea Estate Peak & Viewpoint",category: "Hiking",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best hiked during early morning)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "A breathtakingly scenic peak situated within the historic Hayes Tea Estate, bordering the Sinharaja Rain Forest near Deniyaya and Rakwana. It is a hidden gem among hikers, famous for its sweeping 360-degree panoramic views, cool climate, and dense mist rolling over rolling green tea carpets. The journey to the top takes you through lush tea plantations and offers view of distant mountain ranges, making it an absolute paradise for campers and landscape photographers.",latitude: 6.3858,longitude: 80.6482),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp29.jpg', place: "Hikkaduwa Beach",rate: 4.5,description: "Vibrant Coastal Resort & Marine Sanctuary",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited from November to April)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "One of Sri Lanka's most popular and energetic beach destinations, situated on the southwest coast. It is widely famous for its shallow coral reef marine sanctuary, making it a premier spot for snorkeling, scuba diving, and viewing sea turtles up close. Hikkaduwa is equally celebrated for its excellent surfing breaks, glass-bottom boat tours, vibrant nightlife, and a bustling strip of beachside restaurants, cafes, and souvenir shops.",latitude: 6.1394,longitude: 80.1030),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp30.jpg', place: "Aberdeen Falls",rate: 4.6,description: "Waterfall with a Majestic Rock Backdrop",category: "Waterfalls",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best viewed during daytime before 4:00 PM)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "A spectacular 98-meter (322 feet) high waterfall located in Ginigathena within the Nuwara Eliya district. Named after the Scottish city of Aberdeen, this stunning cascade is formed by the Kehelgamu Oya, a major tributary of the Kelani River. The falls flow against a massive, dark rock wall surrounded by lush green valleys, offering a breathtaking sight. It features a newly built observation deck that provides an easy and safe vantage point for visitors.",latitude: 6.9478,longitude: 80.4991),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp31.jpg', place: "Ambewela",rate: 4.6,description: "Sri Lanka's Picturesque NewZealand",category: "Nature",openingHours: "8:30 AM - 5:30 PM (Ambewela Farm premises hours)",ticketPrice: "LKR 100 - 200 (Locals) / LKR 500 - 1000 (Foreigners) *Applies to farm entrance",fullDescription: "Widely known as 'Little New Zealand,' Ambewela is a beautiful hill country town situated over 6,000 feet above sea level. It is famous for its rolling green pastures, misty landscapes, massive wind turbines, and well-managed dairy farms. Visitors can tour the Ambewela Farm to see premium cattle grazing on lush hills, explore the milk processing plants, buy fresh dairy products like cheese and milkshakes, and enjoy a uniquely cold and refreshing climate.",latitude: 6.8775,longitude: 80.8144),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp32.jpg', place: "Kalpitiya Beach",rate: 4.2,description: "Premier Kitesurfing Hub",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited from May to September for kitesurfing, and November to April for dolphin watching)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "Located on the windswept Kalpitiya Peninsula on the northwest coast of Sri Lanka, Kalpitiya Beach is internationally renowned as one of the top kitesurfing destinations in South Asia. Characterized by its unique geography of lagoons, sand spits, and stable ocean winds, it offers perfect conditions for water sports. Beyond kitesurfing, it is a prime starting point for thrilling marine safaris to spot massive pods of spinner dolphins and whales, as well as exploring vibrant coral reefs through scuba diving and snorkeling.",latitude: 8.2312,longitude: 79.7611),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp33.jpg', place: "Hawagala",rate: 4.8,description: "Scenic Mountain Peak & Camping Site",category: "Hiking",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best hiked starting early morning)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "A breathtaking mountain peak situated in Belihuloya within the Ratnapura district. Rising to an elevation of around 1,400 meters, Hawagala is famous for its unique shape resembling a crouching rabbit, which gives it its name. The trail offers an adventurous hike through pine forests and mana grass fields, leading up to a flat summit. Once at the top, hikers are rewarded with spectacular 360-degree views of the surrounding mountains, including Samanalawewa Reservoir, Haputale, and Horton Plains, making it an absolute favorite destination for overnight camping.",latitude: 6.7412,longitude: 80.7681),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp34.jpg', place: "Knuckles Mountain Range",rate: 4.8,description: "UNESCO World Heritage Cloud Forest",category: "Hiking",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best explored with a local guide during daytime)",ticketPrice: "LKR 100 - 200 (Locals) / USD 10 - 15 (Foreigners) *Department of Forest Conservation permit fees apply at main trailheads",fullDescription: "A stunningly beautiful UNESCO World Heritage site named after its unique silhouette that resembles a clenched fist. Covering a vast area in the central highlands, this mist-laden mountain range features diverse ecosystems, cascading waterfalls, hidden mountain villages like Meemure, and a rich variety of endemic flora and fauna. It is widely considered the ultimate paradise for hikers, campers, and nature enthusiasts in Sri Lanka, offering trails ranging from leisure walks to intense mountain treks.",latitude: 7.4333,longitude: 80.7833),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp35.jpg', place: "Koggala Stilt Fishing",rate: 3.6,description: "Iconic Fishing & Cultural Sight",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "5:30 AM - 7:30 PM (Best viewed during sunrise or sunset when fishermen are active)",ticketPrice: "Free to watch from afar (Fishermen usually request a tip of LKR 500 - 2000 for close-up photographs or to experience sitting on the stilt)",fullDescription: "One of Sri Lanka's most iconic and deeply traditional cultural sights, located along the sandy shores of Koggala on the southern coast. Stilt fishing, locally known as 'Rithi Panna,' is an ancient fishing method unique to the island where fishermen balance skillfully on a crossbar tied to a wooden pole driven deep into the coral reef. Visitors can witness this incredible art, capture world-famous photographs against the backdrop of the Indian Ocean, and even try balancing on the stilts themselves.",latitude: 5.9864,longitude: 80.3225),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp36.jpg', place: "Lipton's Seat",rate: 4.6,description: "Iconic Mountain Overlook & Tea Viewpoint",category: "Nature",openingHours: "6:00 AM - 5:00 PM (Best visited between 6:00 AM and 9:00 AM before mist covers the view)",ticketPrice: "LKR 100 - 200 (Locals) / LKR 500 - 1000 (Foreigners) *Subject to minor local authority or estate updates",fullDescription: "One of Sri Lanka's most spectacular viewpoints, located on the Dambatenne Tea Estate near Haputale. Rising to an elevation of nearly 1,970 meters, it is the famous spot where the legendary tea magnate Sir Thomas Lipton used to sit and survey his vast tea empire. On a clear day, it offers an unparalleled panoramic view that extends across several provinces, emerald green tea valleys, and even towards the southern coast. The journey to the top through beautifully manicured tea plantations is an unforgettable experience.",latitude: 6.7802,longitude: 81.0183),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp37.jpg', place: "Madolsima",rate: 4.7,description: "Misty Mountain Highlands & Mini World's End",category: "Hiking",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited during early morning or evening for camping and view)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "A breathtaking highland region located in the Badulla district, famous for its sweeping mountain ridges, endless pine forests, and a dramatic drop-off known as the Madolsima Mini World's End (Pitamaruwa). Perched over 1,000 meters above sea level, it is a paradise for campers and nature lovers who flock here to witness the spectacular phenomenon of sea of clouds rolling below the cliffs. The misty weather, cool climate, and stunning panoramic views of the eastern plains make it one of the ultimate off-the-beaten-path destinations in Sri Lanka.",latitude: 7.0315,longitude: 81.1611),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp38.jpg', place: "Maha Eliya",rate: 4.7,description: "Historic Montane Plain & Cloud Forest",category: "Hiking",openingHours: "6:00 AM - 4:00 PM (Best visited early morning)",ticketPrice: "LKR 150 - 300 (Locals) / USD 15 - 25 (Foreigners) *Standard Horton Plains National Park entrance fees apply",fullDescription: "Historically known as 'Maha Eliya' (The Great Lawn) before being renamed Horton Plains during the British era, this is a protected national park in the central highlands of Sri Lanka. Situated at an altitude of 2,100–2,300 meters, it is characterized by an undulating plateau covered by montane grasslands and cloud forests. It is a biodiversity hotspot rich in endemic flora and fauna, including Sri Lankan Sambar deer and the purple-faced langur. It also forms the headwaters of three major rivers and hosts the famous World's End drop.",latitude: 6.8028,longitude: 80.8091),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp39.jpg', place: "Mandaramnuwara",rate: 4.7,description: "Misty Mountain Village & Hidden Waterfall",category: "Nature",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited during daytime)",ticketPrice: "Free *Activity or specific waterfall path fees may apply locally",fullDescription: "Commonly known as the 'Misty City' or the 'Shadowed Kingdom,' Mandaramnuwara is a breathtakingly beautiful, isolated mountain village nestled at the foot of Pidurutalagala, Sri Lanka's highest peak. Due to its unique geographical location surrounded by massive mountain walls, the village receives very little direct sunlight and is almost constantly blanketed in thick mist and cool weather. It is a dream destination for nature lovers, offering lush green terraced paddy fields, sprawling tea estates, and easy access to several hidden waterfalls like Kolapathana Ella.",latitude: 7.0253,longitude: 80.7936),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp40.jpg', place: "Mirissa Beach",rate: 4.6,description: "Tropical Beach & Whale Watching",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited from November to April)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "One of the most picturesque and laid-back beach destinations on Sri Lanka's southern coast, shaped like a perfect crescent and lined with swaying coconut palms. Mirissa Beach is world-renowned as a premier hotspot for ocean safaris to spot blue whales, sperm whales, and dolphins. The beach features pristine golden sands, excellent surfing waves, and the famous Coconut Tree Hill viewpoint nearby. As night falls, the shoreline comes alive with beachfront seafood restaurants, ambient lighting, and a vibrant, relaxing nightlife.",latitude: 5.9442,longitude: 80.4578),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp41.jpg', place: "Nanuoya Falls",rate: 4.6,description: "Cascading Multi-Tiered Waterfall",category: "Waterfalls",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best viewed during daytime)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "A beautiful multi-tiered waterfall situated in Nanuoya, just a few kilometers away from Nuwara Eliya town. The waterfall cascades gracefully down a series of natural stone steps and passes right under the historic railway line bridge. It is heavily fed by the Nanu Oya river and offers a highly refreshing and picturesque sight, especially for travelers taking the iconic highland train ride or exploring the misty tea estate trails nearby.",latitude: 6.9458,longitude: 80.7389),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp42.jpg', place: "Negombo Beach",rate: 4.2,description: "Broad Golden Shoreline & Lively Coastal Strip",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited during late afternoon for sunset views)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "A wide, expansive stretch of golden sand located on the western coast of Sri Lanka, just a short drive from the international airport. Known for its historical fishing charm and vibrant tourist strip, Negombo Beach is lined with popular luxury resorts, boutique hotels, seafood restaurants, and lively pubs. While the sea can have strong currents, the beach is highly celebrated for its spectacular sunset vistas, beach volleyball, traditional catamaran boat rides, and relaxing evening strolls.",latitude: 7.2215,longitude: 79.8407),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp43.jpg', place: "Nilaveli Beach",rate: 4.5,description: "Pristine White-Sand Shoreline",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited from May to September when the sea is calmest)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "Widely regarded as one of the most beautiful and pristine beaches in Sri Lanka, Nilaveli is located on the eastern coast near Trincomalee. It is famous for its long, wide stretches of soft white sand and calm, crystal-clear turquoise waters that are perfect for swimming, sunbathing, and relaxation. The beach serves as the primary gateway and boat launch point for visitors traveling to the nearby Pigeon Island National Park, which is one of the country's best marine sanctuaries for snorkeling and viewing live coral reefs and sea turtles.",latitude: 8.6875,longitude: 81.1891),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp44.jpg', place: "Nuwara Eliya",rate: 4.6,description: "Sri Lanka's 'Little England' Resort Town",category: "Nature",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited year-round, with April being the peak festive season)",ticketPrice: "Free *Entrance fees apply separately for specific parks, gardens, or boat rides",fullDescription: "Nestled at an elevation of 1,868 meters in the central highlands, Nuwara Eliya is the coolest and most famous hill country resort in Sri Lanka. Dubbed 'Little England' due to its chilly mountain climate, colonial-era bungalows, manicured lawns, and red-brick post office, the town is a picturesque escape surrounded by endless tea plantations. Key landmarks include Gregory Lake, Victoria Park, Hakgala Botanical Gardens, and the historic golf club. It is the heart of the island's tea industry and offers a beautifully nostalgic atmosphere filled with mist and fresh mountain air.",latitude: 6.9497,longitude: 80.7891),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp45.jpg', place: "Parakrama Samudra",rate: 4.8,description: "Ancient Reservoir & Engineering Marvel",category: "Historical",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited during late afternoon for sunset views)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "One of the greatest ancient engineering feats of Sri Lanka, the Parakrama Samudra is a massive man-made reservoir located in Polonnaruwa. Built by King Parakramabahu the Great, it consists of five separate lakes connected together to look like a vast sea, earning it the name 'Samudra.' It was constructed to store rainwater and support a vast network of irrigation for agricultural flourishing, embodying the king's famous decree that 'not even a single drop of water from rain should flow into the ocean without being useful to man.' Today, it is famous for its breathtaking sunsets, cool lake breezes, and rich wildlife.",latitude: 7.9258,longitude: 81.0022),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp46.jpg', place: "Peradeniya Botanical Garden",rate: 4.7,description: "Sri Lanka's Largest Botanical Garden",category: "Nature",openingHours: "7:30 AM - 5:00 PM (Open 365 days a year)",ticketPrice: "LKR 100 - 200 (Locals) / LKR 3000 (Foreigners) *Prices subject to change based on department updates",fullDescription: "Renowned as the finest botanical garden in Sri Lanka and one of the best in Asia, the Royal Botanical Gardens in Peradeniya dates back to the Kandyan Kingdom era. Spanning across 147 acres and bounded by the scenic Mahaweli River, it houses a stunning collection of over 4,000 species of plants, including orchids, medicinal herbs, spices, and towering palm trees. Famous highlights include the spectacular Orchid House, the iconic Avenue of Royal Palms, the massive Javan Fig tree, and peaceful walking pathways that attract nature lovers, researchers, and tourists worldwide.",latitude: 7.2681,longitude: 80.5966),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp47.jpg', place: "Pidurangala",rate: 4.8,description: "Historic Rock Fortress & Viewpoint",category: "Religious",openingHours: "5:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best hiked starting around 5:00 AM for sunrise views)",ticketPrice: "LKR 1,000 (For Foreigners) / Around LKR 100 - 200 (For Locals) *Collected at the temple entrance fee counter",fullDescription: "A massive rock formation located just a few kilometers north of the famous Sigiriya Rock Fortress. Pidurangala has a deep history dating back to the reign of King Kashyapa, who built a royal Buddhist temple complex here to relocate the monks who were previously on Sigiriya Rock. The hike to the top takes you through ancient temple ruins, a reclining Buddha statue inside a historic cave, and a challenging final boulder scramble. Once at the flat summit, visitors are treated to an unparalleled, jaw-dropping panoramic view of the Sigiriya Citadel rising out of the lush green jungle canopy.",latitude: 7.9628,longitude: 80.7642),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp48.jpg', place: "Pigeon Island",rate: 3.9,description: "Marine National Park & Snorkeling Hotspot",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "8:00 AM - 4:00 PM (Best visited from May to September when the sea is calm)",ticketPrice: "LKR 300 - 500 (Locals) / USD 25 - 35 (Foreigners) *Excludes boat rental charges from Nilaveli beach and gear rental costs",fullDescription: "One of the two marine national parks in Sri Lanka, Pigeon Island is a beautiful coral island situated just 1 kilometer off the coastal town of Nilaveli in Trincomalee. The park derives its name from the thousands of rock pigeons that colonize and breed on it. It is widely considered a world-class hotspot for snorkeling and scuba diving, boasting some of the best-preserved live coral reefs on the island. Visitors can effortlessly swim alongside a rich variety of colorful reef fish, blacktip reef sharks, and large sea turtles in crystal-clear turquoise waters.",latitude: 8.7214,longitude: 81.2012),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp49.jpg', place: "Pitawala Pathana",rate: 4.7,description: "Ecological Grassland & Sheer Cliff View",category: "Hiking",openingHours: "6:00 AM - 5:00 PM (Best visited early morning before it gets too hot or covered in thick mist)",ticketPrice: "LKR 100 - 200 (Locals) / Around LKR 1000 (Foreigners) *Standard forest department entrance fees apply",fullDescription: "An incredibly unique, natural grassland plain covering about 10 hectares situated inside the Knuckles Conservation Forest in Matale. Unlike typical plains, it is characterized by a very thin layer of soil over a vast rock base, allowing only a specific type of short grass and rare endemic flora/fauna to survive. The major highlight here is the Pitawala Pathana Mini World's End, a jaw-dropping sheer cliff that drops vertically for several hundred meters, offering a spectacular panoramic view of the Knuckles mountain range, valleys, and villages below.",latitude: 7.5106,longitude: 80.7431),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp50.jpg', place: "Polonnaruwa",rate: 4.8,description: "UNESCO World Heritage Site",category: "Historical",openingHours: "7:00 AM - 5:30 PM (Best explored during cooler morning or late afternoon hours)",ticketPrice: "LKR 100 - 150 (Locals) / USD 25 - 30 (Foreigners) *Covers entry to all main archaeological sites and museum",fullDescription: "Steeped in rich history, Polonnaruwa was the second oldest kingdom of Sri Lanka, flourishing as a grand medieval capital between the 11th and 13th centuries. Declared a UNESCO World Heritage site, it showcases a beautifully preserved ancient city filled with monumental ruins, stupas, and palaces built by great rulers like King Vijayabahu I and King Parakramabahu the Great. Key architectural wonders include the Royal Palace, the beautiful Vatadage in the Quadrangle, the massive Rankot Vihara stupa, and the world-famous Gal Vihara, which features four magnificent Buddha statues intricately carved out of a single granite rock face.",latitude: 7.9403,longitude: 81.0028),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp51.jpg', place: "Rangala Ella",rate: 4.4,description: "Hidden Waterfall & Deep Turquoise Rock Pool",category: "Waterfalls",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited during daytime, avoiding heavy rainy seasons)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "A beautiful hidden gem located in the Rangala village near Teldeniya, nestled inside the foothills of the Knuckles Mountain Range. Fed by the pristine mountain streams of the Kotaganga river network, the waterfall cascades through massive boulders and collects into a deep, crystal-clear turquoise natural rock pool underneath. While it is incredibly picturesque and a popular spot for relaxing photography, the pool is known for its treacherous depth and strong undercurrents, making swimming dangerous. The surrounding lush green forest and tea estates make the journey here highly refreshing.",latitude: 7.3719,longitude: 80.7681),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp52.jpg', place: "Jami Ul-Alfar Mosque",rate: 4.6,description: "Iconic Red & White Candy-Striped Facade",category: "Religious",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited during non-prayer times)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "Widely known as the 'Red Mosque' or 'Pettah Red Masjid,' this stunning building is one of the most iconic landmarks in Colombo. Located in the heart of the bustling Pettah market district, it was built in 1909 and is famous for its unique Indo-Islamic architectural style, characterized by a striking, candy-striped facade of bright red and white bricks. The intricate design and distinctive minarets make it a masterpiece of colonial-era architecture and a must-visit spot for photography enthusiasts and tourists exploring the history of Colombo.",latitude: 6.9367,longitude: 79.8475),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp53.jpg', place: "Ruwanweliseya",rate: 4.9,description: "Masterpiece of Ancient Buddhist Architecture",category: "Religious",openingHours: "5:30 AM - 9:00 PM (Best visited during early morning or evening to avoid hot stone floors)",ticketPrice: "Free *For locals. Foreigners usually pay the standard Anuradhapura ancient city cultural triangle ticket fee.",fullDescription: "One of the world's most sacred and monumental Buddhist structures, the Ruwanweliseya is a magnificent stupa built by the legendary King Dutugemunu in 140 BC. Standing as a focal point of the Solosmasthana (the 16 sacred places) in Anuradhapura, it is renowned for its architectural grandeur and its massive base surrounded by a wall adorned with hundreds of beautifully carved elephants. The stupa enshrines a large quantity of Lord Buddha's relics, drawing millions of pilgrims and travelers from around the globe who come to witness its serene, glowing white dome and experience the deep spiritual tranquility of the site.",latitude: 8.3501,longitude: 80.3964),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp54.jpg', place: "Sembuwatta Lake",rate: 4.5,description: "Mirror-Like Mountain Lake & Pine Forests",category: "Nature",openingHours: "8:00 AM - 5:00 PM (Best visited during mid-morning when the mist clears up)",ticketPrice: "Around LKR 200 - 300 (For Locals) / Around LKR 1000 (For Foreigners) *Subject to estate management updates",fullDescription: "A breathtaking man-made lake nestled deep within the lush green hills of the Campbell’s Lane Forest Reserve in Elkaduwa, Matale. Originally created as a reservoir for generating electricity for the surrounding tea factory, Sembuwatta has transformed into a premier eco-tourism destination. The lake is famous for its glassy, emerald-green waters that beautifully mirror the towering pine trees and rolling tea hills enveloping it. It features well-maintained walking pathways, cozy summer huts, adventure activities like zip-lining, and a natural spring-fed swimming pool nearby.",latitude: 7.4431,longitude: 80.6953),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp55.jpg', place: "Sera Ella",rate: 4.7,description: "Twin Cascade with a Hidden Walk-In Cave",category: "Waterfalls",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited during daytime, ideally from November to January post-monsoon)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "One of the most unique and captivating waterfalls in Sri Lanka, Sera Ella is hidden deep within the Knuckles Conservation Forest near Ilukkumbura. The waterfall is famous for its wide, sheet-like twin cascades that tumble down a massive, flat rock face. What sets it completely apart is the cool, damp rock cave situated directly behind the falling curtain of water. A well-constructed safety pathway allows visitors to walk right into this hidden cavern, offering a spectacular and misty view of the forest looking outwards through the rushing water cascade.",latitude: 7.5819,longitude: 80.7583),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp56.jpg', place: "St. Clair's Falls",rate: 4.7,description: "The Majestic 'Niagara of Sri Lanka'",category: "Waterfalls",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best viewed from the main road viewing deck during daytime)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "Commonly referred to as the 'Niagara of Sri Lanka' due to its incredible width and volume, St. Clair's Falls is one of the most stunning and famous waterfalls in the country. Located along the Hatton-Talawakele road, it cascades down a series of rock ledges in two distinct tiers: the 'Maha Ella' (Greater Fall) and 'Kuda Ella' (Lesser Fall). Nestled amid rolling green tea valleys and misty mountain backdrops, the waterfall is effortlessly visible from a dedicated viewing deck on the main highway, making it an iconic and essential stop for travelers exploring the central highlands.",latitude: 6.9367,longitude: 80.6289),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp57.jpg', place: "Trincomalee Sea",rate: 4.6,description: "Deep Blue Waters & World-Class Marine Explorer",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Whale watching and boat tours are best booked from May to September)",ticketPrice: "Free *Boat safaris and marine tours operate under separate private or wildlife department fees",fullDescription: "The sea and coastline around Trincomalee are legendary for having some of the deepest and most pristine blue waters in the Indian Ocean. Home to one of the world's largest natural harbors, this coastal stretch offers much more than just beautiful beaches like Nilaveli and Uppuveli. It is a premier global destination for whale and dolphin watching, where visitors can frequently spot magnificent Blue Whales and Sperm Whales just a few miles off the shore. The crystal-clear marine environment is also highly celebrated for scuba diving, shipwreck exploration, and deep-sea fishing.",latitude: 8.5711,longitude: 81.2336),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp58.jpg', place: "Udawalawe National Park",rate: 4.6,description: "Wild Elephant Sightings & Pristine Wilderness",category: "Wildlife",openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best visited during early morning at 6:00 AM or late afternoon at 3:00 PM for optimal animal sightings)",ticketPrice: "LKR 150 - 250 (Locals) / USD 25 - 30 (Foreigners) *Excludes mandatory safari jeep hiring fees and department service charges",fullDescription: "Located on the boundary of the Sabaragamuwa and Uva provinces, Udawalawe National Park is an incredibly important habitat for Sri Lankan elephants and one of the best places in Asia to see them in the wild. Centered around the massive Udawalawe reservoir, the park features vast open grasslands and bush forests, making wildlife spotting remarkably easy. It is home to a thriving population of over 250 elephants, alongside leopards, sloth bears, water buffaloes, and countless species of exotic birds. A key highlight adjacent to the park is the Udawalawe Elephant Transit Home, where orphaned elephant calves are cared for and rehabilitated back into the wild.",latitude: 6.4741,longitude: 80.8922),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp59.jpg', place: "Uda Diyaluma",rate: 4.8,description: "Breathtaking Natural Infinity Pools",category: "Waterfalls",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best hiked during early morning daylight hours; strictly avoid hiking during heavy rains or after dark)",ticketPrice: "Free *Local guides may charge a small fee if you choose to hire them for the trail",fullDescription: "Uda Diyaluma refers to the spectacular upper section of Diyaluma Falls, the second-highest waterfall in Sri Lanka, located near Koslanda in the Badulla District. Reached via a scenic trek through rubber estates and tall grasslands, the summit offers an entirely different experience than the view from the roadside below. It features a series of smaller cascading waterfalls that carve out pristine, crystal-clear natural rock pools. These pools sit directly at the precipice where the water plunges down hundreds of feet, creating breathtaking, natural 'infinity pools' that provide panoramic views of the surrounding valleys and mountains.",latitude: 6.7328,longitude: 81.0285),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp60.jpg', place: "Unawatuna Beach",rate: 4.5,description: "World-Famous Banana-Shaped Golden Beach",category: "Beaches",openingHours: "Open 24 Hours (Best visited for swimming during daytime and relaxing at beach cafes by sunset)",ticketPrice: "Free",fullDescription: "One of the most famous and picturesque coastal stretches in Sri Lanka, Unawatuna Beach is renowned for its unique banana-shaped coastline lined with swaying palm trees and golden sand. Situated just a few kilometers south of the historic city of Galle, its calm blue waters are protected by a coral reef, making it an incredibly safe and popular spot for swimming, snorkeling, and scuba diving. The beachfront is famous for its vibrant atmosphere, bursting with a lively array of cozy cafes, seafood restaurants, and trendy boutique hotels, making it a favorite destination for both relaxation and coastal nightlife.",latitude: 6.0174,longitude: 80.2489),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp61.jpg', place: "Maduru Oya National Park", rate: 4.5, description: "Wildlife Sanctuary & Reservoir", category: "Wildlife", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM", ticketPrice: "USD 15 - 25 (Foreigners) / LKR 150 - 250 (Locals) + Service & Vehicle Fees", fullDescription: "Established in 1983 to protect the catchment area of the Maduru Oya Reservoir, this national park is a critical sanctuary for Sri Lankan elephants. It features unique rock formations, ruins of ancient sluice gates, and provides a habitat for diverse wildlife including leopards, sloth bears, and various endemic bird species.", latitude: 7.6492, longitude: 81.1895),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp62.jpg', place: "Jungle Beach", rate: 4.2, description: "Secluded Beach & Snorkeling Spot", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "24/7 (Best visited: 8:00 AM - 5:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "A small, secluded bay hidden by the dense forest of the Rumassala hill near Unawatuna. Known for its tranquil environment and calm, crystal-clear waters, it is a fantastic location for safe swimming, sunbathing, and snorkeling along the nearby coral reefs. It offers a peaceful escape from the main tourist beaches.", latitude: 6.0183, longitude: 80.2415),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp63.jpg', place: "Kalpitiya Lagoon", rate: 4.7, description: "World-Class Kitesurfing Destination", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:30 PM (Best season: May - October & December - February)", ticketPrice: "Free to visit (Kitesurfing lessons/equipment rental fees vary from USD 30 - 80+)", fullDescription: "Kalpitiya Lagoon is globally renowned as Sri Lanka's premier kitesurfing hotspot, offering flat waters and consistently strong, reliable winds. It caters to both beginners and advanced riders. The surrounding peninsula separates the calm lagoon from the Indian Ocean, making it an ideal environment for water sports, dolphin watching, and beach camping.", latitude: 8.2323, longitude: 79.7618),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp64.jpg', place: "Kelani River, Kitulgala", rate: 4.6, description: "White Water Rafting Hub", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "8:00 AM - 5:30 PM", ticketPrice: "Free to visit (Rafting packages vary from USD 15 - 35 / LKR 3,000 - 8,000+ per person)", fullDescription: "Flowing through the adventure capital of Sri Lanka, the Kelani River in Kitulgala is world-renowned for white water rafting. It features major rapids and minor rapids suitable for both beginners and experienced rafters. The scenic river run carries you through lush tropical rainforests, offering a thrilling mix of adrenaline and natural beauty, alongside options for canyoning and jungle trekking.", latitude: 6.9942, longitude: 80.4144),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp65.jpg', place: "Koggala Lake", rate: 4.5, description: "Scenic Lagoon & Kayaking Destination", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best for sunrise or sunset)", ticketPrice: "Free to visit (Kayaking & boat tours vary from USD 15 - 30 / LKR 3,500 - 7,000+ per boat)", fullDescription: "Koggala Lake is a beautiful, expansive lagoon dotted with lush green islands, including the famous Cinnamon Island. It is a fantastic destination for kayaking, allowing adventure seekers to paddle through serene mangrove tunnels, spot rich birdlife, and experience local prawn fishing traditions in a calm and tranquil environment.", latitude: 5.9961, longitude: 80.3421),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp66.jpg', place: "Lanka Ella Waterfall", rate: 4.6, description: "Unique Map-Shaped Waterfall", category: "Waterfalls", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 5:00 PM (Best visited before afternoon)", ticketPrice: "Free (Local guide fees may apply if hired)", fullDescription: "Lanka Ella is a hidden gem famous for its unique natural formation, where the cascading water and the rock pool below perfectly resemble the geographical shape of Sri Lanka. Situated in the serene Bambarella region, reaching this breathtaking waterfall requires a scenic trek through lush tea plantations and cloud forests, making it a favorite spot for hikers and nature lovers.", latitude: 7.4125, longitude: 80.7850),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp67.jpg', place: "Gal Oya National Park", rate: 4.6, description: "Famous for Swimming Elephants & Boat Safaris", category: "Wildlife", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM", ticketPrice: "USD 15 - 25 (Foreigners) / LKR 150 - 250 (Locals) + Boat & Service Fees", fullDescription: "Established in 1954 to protect the catchment area of the massive Senanayake Samudra reservoir, Gal Oya National Park is uniquely famous for its boat safaris. It offers visitors the rare opportunity to witness herds of elephants swimming between islands in the reservoir. The park is also a sanctuary for leopards, sloth bears, deer, and a rich variety of colorful bird species.", latitude: 7.2140, longitude: 81.4725),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp68.jpg', place: "Negombo Lagoon", rate: 4.3, description: "Vibrant Estuary & Boat Safari Destination", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best for early morning boat rides)", ticketPrice: "Free to visit (Boat tours range from USD 15 - 30 / LKR 4,000 - 8,000+ per boat)", fullDescription: "Negombo Lagoon is a massive semi-enclosed coastal body of water, famous for its traditional fishing culture and extensive mangrove swamps. It is a prime destination for boat safaris, allowing travelers to navigate through peaceful water channels, observe diverse water birds, spot monitor lizards, and see local fishermen using traditional catamarans (oruva) to catch crabs and prawns.", latitude: 7.1689, longitude: 79.8436),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp69.jpg', place: "Bundala National Park", rate: 4.5, description: "UNESCO Biosphere Reserve & Bird Paradise", category: "Wildlife", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM", ticketPrice: "USD 15 - 25 (Foreigners) / LKR 150 - 250 (Locals) + Service & Vehicle Fees", fullDescription: "Bundala National Park is an internationally renowned wetland sanctuary and Sri Lanka's first Ramsar site. It serves as a vital wintering ground for migratory waterbirds, famously hosting large flocks of Greater Flamingos. The park's diverse ecosystem of lagoons, beaches, and thorny scrublands is also home to crocodiles, elephants, leopards, and sea turtles.", latitude: 6.1360, longitude: 81.1895),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp70.jpg', place: "Udawalawe National Park", rate: 4.7, description: "Premier Elephant Sanctuary", category: "Wildlife", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM", ticketPrice: "USD 15 - 25 (Foreigners) / LKR 150 - 250 (Locals) + Service & Vehicle Fees", fullDescription: "Udawalawe National Park is one of Sri Lanka's most popular wildlife destinations, famous for its guaranteed, year-round sightings of wild Sri Lankan elephants. Centered around the massive Udawalawe Reservoir, its open grassland habitat makes it incredibly easy to spot large herds. It provides a vital sanctuary for water birds, water buffaloes, leopards, and crocodiles, and sits adjacent to the Elephant Transit Home.", latitude: 6.4746, longitude: 80.8930),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp71.jpg', place: "Wasgamuwa National Park", rate: 4.4, description: "Haven for Marsh Elephants & Wilderness", category: "Wildlife", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM", ticketPrice: "USD 15 - 25 (Foreigners) / LKR 150 - 250 (Locals) + Service & Vehicle Fees", fullDescription: "Bordered by the Mahaweli and Amban rivers, Wasgamuwa National Park is highly regarded for its untouched wilderness and high biodiversity. It is particularly famous for its large herds of Sri Lankan elephants, known locally for their distinct behaviors. The park also shelters rare wildlife such as sloth bears, leopards, purple-faced langurs, and features historical ruins like the Buduruwayaya Buddha statue.", latitude: 7.7288, longitude: 80.9392),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp72.jpg', place: "Weligama", rate: 4.6, description: "Sandy Surf Bay & Beginner Paradise", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "24/7 (Best for surfing: 6:00 AM - 6:30 PM / Best season: October - April)", ticketPrice: "Free to visit (Surfboard rentals vary from USD 2 - 5 per hour / Lessons range from USD 15 - 30+)", fullDescription: "Weligama Beach is a sprawling, crescent-shaped bay situated along Sri Lanka's southern coast, globally celebrated as the ultimate destination for beginner and intermediate surfers. Its soft sandy bottom, gentle beach breaks, and consistent waves provide a safe and highly encouraging environment for learning water sports. The vibrant coastline is lined with surf schools, lively beach cafes, and boutique hotels.", latitude: 5.9729, longitude: 80.4284),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp73.jpg', place: "Kumana Bird Sanctuary", rate: 4.6, description: "Premier Wetland & Bird Watching Paradise", category: "Wildlife", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM", ticketPrice: "USD 15 - 25 (Foreigners) / LKR 150 - 250 (Locals) + Service & Vehicle Fees", fullDescription: "An integral part of Kumana National Park, the Kumana Bird Sanctuary is one of Sri Lanka's most significant wetland ecosystems. Centered around the 200-hectare Kumana Villu mangrove swamp, it serves as a crucial nesting and breeding ground for thousands of migratory and resident waterfowl. Visitors can witness spectacular gatherings of painted storks, pelicans, herons, and rare black-necked storks.", latitude: 6.5167, longitude: 81.6833),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp74.jpg', place: "Bambarakanda Falls", rate: 4.7, description: "The Tallest Waterfall in Sri Lanka", category: "Waterfalls", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 5:00 PM", ticketPrice: "Free (LKR 30 - 50 for ticket counter near the pine forest trail if entering the base area)", fullDescription: "Plunging from a staggering height of 263 meters (863 feet), Bambarakanda Falls is the highest waterfall in Sri Lanka and ranks as the 299th highest in the world. Formed by a tributary of the Walawe River, it cascades down a sheer vertical cliff surrounded by a dense pine forest in Kalupahana. Reaching the base involves a short, scenic trek through lush vegetation, offering breathtaking photography opportunities.", latitude: 6.7725, longitude: 80.8322),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp75.jpg', place: "Minneriya National Park", rate: 4.6, description: "Home of the Famous Elephant Gathering", category: "Wildlife", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best safari time: 3:00 PM - 6:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "USD 15 - 25 (Foreigners) / LKR 150 - 250 (Locals) + Service & Vehicle Fees", fullDescription: "Minneriya National Park is a world-renowned wildlife sanctuary located in the North Central Province. It is globally famous for 'The Gathering,' an incredible seasonal phenomenon between July and October where hundreds of wild Asian elephants congregate around the ancient Minneriya Tank to feed and bathe. The park also shelters leopards, sloth bears, axis deer, and over 160 species of birds.", latitude: 8.0305, longitude: 80.8229),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp76.jpg', place: "Bathalegala", rate: 4.6, description: "Scenic Flat-Topped Mountain (Bible Rock)", category: "Hiking", openingHours: "24/7 (Best for morning hikes: 5:30 AM - 5:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "Bathalegala, widely known as Bible Rock due to its striking resemblance to an open book, is a prominent flat-topped mountain near Mawanella. Rising about 790 meters above sea level, it offers a relatively easy yet highly rewarding hike through rubber plantations and lush greenery. The summit features breathtaking 360-degree panoramic views of the surrounding mountains, including Sri Pada and Asupini Ella, along with a small Buddhist temple.", latitude: 7.1917, longitude: 80.4356),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp77.jpg', place: "Batticaloa Lagoon", rate: 4.4, description: "Famous for Singing Fish & Boat Safaris", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best visited during sunrise or sunset)", ticketPrice: "Free to visit (Boat safari rates vary from USD 15 - 30 / LKR 4,500 - 8,500+ per boat)", fullDescription: "Batticaloa Lagoon is a massive, picturesque body of water in eastern Sri Lanka, famous for the legendary 'singing fish' musical sounds heard on full moon nights between April and September. Taking a scenic boat safari through the lagoon allows visitors to explore extensive mangrove eco-systems, spot endemic water birds, view the historic Batticaloa Fort, and pass underneath iconic local bridges.", latitude: 7.7167, longitude: 81.6994),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp78.jpg', place: "Bentota Lagoon", rate: 4.5, description: "Water Sports Capital & Scenic Estuary", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best for water sports and boat safaris)", ticketPrice: "Free to visit (Jet ski, banana boat, and boat safari rates vary from USD 15 - 40+)", fullDescription: "Bentota Lagoon is a stunning coastal body of water where the Bentota River meets the Indian Ocean. Enclosed by a dramatic sandy peninsula, it is widely considered the ultimate hub for thrill-seekers, offering activities like jet skiing, windsurfing, water skiing, and banana boat rides. For a calmer experience, visitors can take scenic boat cruises through dense mangrove tunnels to observe crocodiles, water monitors, and exotic birds.", latitude: 6.4253, longitude: 79.9972),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp79.jpg', place: "Bopath Ella Waterfall", rate: 4.4, description: "Bo-Leaf Shaped Cascade", category: "Waterfalls", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM", ticketPrice: "Free (LKR 50 - 100 environmental fee may be collected at the entrance area)", fullDescription: "Bopath Ella is a highly popular and easily accessible waterfall famous for its unique shape that perfectly resembles a sacred Bo leaf. Standing at roughly 30 meters high, the waterfall is formed by the Kuru Ganga and cascades down a narrow opening before widening spectacularly at the base. It is surrounded by lush green foliage and offers a pleasant day trip destination, complete with myths about hidden treasures under the falls.", latitude: 6.7269, longitude: 80.3644),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp80.jpg', place: "Castlereagh Reservoir", rate: 4.8, description: "Serene Alpine Reservoir & Kayaking Spot", category: "Water Sports", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best for mist-covered morning paddles)", ticketPrice: "Free to visit (Kayaking equipment & boat rentals are usually arranged via lakeside luxury resorts/bungalows, fees vary)", fullDescription: "Nestled deeply within the lush tea country of Hatton, Castlereagh Reservoir is a breathtakingly beautiful body of turquoise water surrounded by emerald-green hills and misty pine forests. Kayaking here offers a deeply peaceful adventure, away from roaring water sports, allowing travelers to glide across glassy waters, enjoy spectacular views of the classic Christ Church Warleigh, and witness sea planes landing gracefully on the reservoir.", latitude: 6.8642, longitude: 80.5639),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp81.jpg', place: "Devil's Staircase", rate: 4.8, description: "Thrilling Mountain Trail & Extreme Hike", category: "Hiking", openingHours: "24/7 (Best traveled during daylight: 6:00 AM - 4:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free (4x4 vehicle rentals or guide fees vary if hired)", fullDescription: "The Devil's Staircase is one of Sri Lanka's most treacherous yet staggeringly beautiful mountain trails, stretching roughly 14 kilometers between Kalupahana and Ohiya. Known for its intense hairpin turns, steep drop-offs, and rugged terrain, it offers adventurers an unforgettable route through vast tea estates, mist-laden pine hills, and iconic landmarks like the 'V-Cut' and Bambarakanda Falls.", latitude: 6.7914, longitude: 80.8266),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp82.jpg', place: "Devon Falls", rate: 4.7, description: "The Veil of the Valley Waterfall", category: "Waterfalls", openingHours: "24/7 (Best viewed from the main road viewpoint during daylight: 6:00 AM - 6:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "Devon Falls, dropping dramatically from a height of 97 meters (318 feet), is one of the most striking and iconic waterfalls in Sri Lanka. Named after a pioneer English coffee planter named Devon whose estate was nearby, the multi-tiered cascade cuts through a backdrop of lush green tea plantations. It is perfectly observed from the popular Devon Viewpoint along the Avissawella-Hatton-Nuwara Eliya Highway, where a refreshing breeze always awaits travelers.", latitude: 6.9372, longitude: 80.6277),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp83.jpg', place: "Gerandi Ella Falls", rate: 4.6, description: "Massive Multi-Tiered Mountain Cascade", category: "Waterfalls", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 5:00 PM (Best for hiking during dry days)", ticketPrice: "Free (Guide fees may apply if taking the advanced trekking routes)", fullDescription: "Gerandi Ella is a spectacular, massive waterfall located in Kalugala, near Ududumbara in the Kandy District. Dropping from a height of approximately 100 meters, it cascades down a sheer vertical rock face in multiple segments, looking remarkably like a crawling rat snake (Gerandiya) from a distance. The hike to the upper tiers and the viewpoint offers an adventurous trail through dense vegetation, rock scrambles, and rewards hikers with sweeping views of the Knuckles Mountain Range.", latitude: 7.3402, longitude: 80.8715),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp84.jpg', place: "Great Western Mountain", rate: 4.7, description: "Sri Lanka's Sixth Highest Mountain Peak", category: "Hiking", openingHours: "24/7 (Highly recommended to start hiking by 5:30 AM - 6:00 AM)", ticketPrice: "Free (Local guide fees vary if hired for safety)", fullDescription: "Great Western Mountain is a majestic, wall-like mountain ridge rising to an elevation of 2,212 meters in the Nuwara Eliya District. The steep and adventurous trail starts near the historic Great Western railway station, leading hikers through beautiful tea estates, dense pine forests, and misty cloud forests. The summit offers incredibly rewarding views of the surrounding central highlands, railway lines, and neighboring valleys, making it a favorite among experienced trekkers.", latitude: 6.9658, longitude: 80.6978),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp85.jpg', place: "Haritha Kanda", rate: 4.6, description: "Lush Green Rolling Hills & Camping Site", category: "Hiking", openingHours: "24/7 (Best to hike during daylight: 6:00 AM - 5:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free (Camping may require local permission or estate entry awareness)", fullDescription: "True to its name, which translates to 'Green Mountain,' Haritha Kanda is a stunningly vibrant, emerald-green mountain ridge located near Bogawantalawa. Characterized by its rolling plains, soft grassy slopes, and misty backdrop, it offers a relatively moderate hike that is highly popular among campers and nature enthusiasts. The misty summit feels like an untouched paradise, providing sweeping views of the surrounding tea valleys and distant mountain ranges.", latitude: 6.7845, longitude: 80.6812),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp86.jpg', place: "Alagalla Mountain Range", rate: 4.7, description: "Historic Defensive Peak & Potato Rock", category: "Hiking", openingHours: "24/7 (Best to start trekking around 6:00 AM - 7:00 AM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "Alagalla Mountain Range, famously known as Potato Rock during the British colonial era, stands majestically at the borders of the Central and Sabaragamuwa provinces. Historically serving as a natural defensive lookout point for the Kandyan Kingdom against foreign invasions, it is now a highly sought-after destination for trekkers. The trail cuts through tea patches and steep rocky terrains, leading to a summit that treats hikers to astonishing panoramic views of Utuwankanda, Bathalegala, and passing trains below.", latitude: 7.2792, longitude: 80.4853),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp87.jpg', place: "Bentota Beach", rate: 4.6, description: "Golden Sand Paradise & Resort Hub", category: "Beaches", openingHours: "24/7 (Best for swimming and sunsets: 6:00 AM - 6:30 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "Bentota Beach is a world-class stretch of golden shoreline situated on the southwest coast of Sri Lanka. Blessed with calm, azure waters and shaded by endless groves of tall coconut palms, it is the perfect destination for sunbathing, swimming, and romantic sunset strolls. The beach is flanked by luxury boutique resorts and sits adjacent to the Bentota Lagoon, making it an ideal tropical escape.", latitude: 6.4276, longitude: 79.9944),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp88.jpg', place: "Browns Beach", rate: 4.2, description: "Vibrant Coastal Strip in Negombo", category: "Beaches", openingHours: "24/7 (Best for evening walks and street food: 4:30 PM - 9:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "Browns Beach is a popular and lively sandy shore located along the coastal stretch of Negombo. Known for its wide sandy beachfront and bustling atmosphere, it is a favorite spot for evening strolls, beach volleyball, and catching beautiful ocean sunsets. The beachside is lined with numerous hotels, seafood restaurants, and local street food stalls selling fresh bites, making it a highly energetic hub for travelers.", latitude: 7.2285, longitude: 79.8398),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp89.jpg', place: "Goyambokka Beach", rate: 4.6, description: "Secluded Bay & Turquoise Waters", category: "Beaches", openingHours: "24/7 (Best for swimming and sunbathing: 7:00 AM - 6:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "Goyambokka Beach is a hidden gem tucked away in Tangalle on the southern coast of Sri Lanka. Characterized by its soft golden sand, brilliant turquoise waters, and a curved bay lined with lush coconut palms and massive granite boulders, it offers a peaceful, tropical paradise vibe. It is relatively quieter than other mainstream commercial beaches, making it an excellent spot for relaxing, swimming in calmer areas, and enjoying fresh seafood at local beach shacks.", latitude: 6.0152, longitude: 80.7769),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp90.jpg', place: "Hiriketiya Beach", rate: 4.7, description: "Surfers' Paradise & Horseshoe Bay", category: "Beaches", openingHours: "24/7 (Best for surfing and beach vibes: 6:00 AM - 7:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free (Surfboard rentals vary from LKR 500 - 1000 per hour)", fullDescription: "Hiriketiya Beach, also known as Hiriketiya Bay, is a gorgeous horseshoe-shaped jungle beach located in Dikwella. Famed for its unique microclimate and consistent year-round surf breaks, it attracts both beginner and intermediate surfers from around the globe. The shore is lined with trendy cafes, yoga studios, and overhanging coconut palms, giving it a distinctively laid-back, bohemian tropical atmosphere.", latitude: 5.9649, longitude: 80.6083),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp91.jpg', place: "Madu Ganga", rate: 4.6, description: "Ramsar Wetland & Mangrove Safari", category: "Nature", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best for morning or late afternoon boat rides)", ticketPrice: "Free to visit the area (Boat safari tours cost around LKR 4,500 - 8,000+ per boat depending on the duration)", fullDescription: "Madu Ganga is a pristine coastal wetland estuary located in Balapitiya, spanning over 900 hectares and dotted with 64 small islands. Recognized as a Ramsar Wetland due to its rich biodiversity, it features dense, beautiful mangrove tunnels that boats glide through. A typical safari includes visiting a cinnamon cultivation island, exploring the ancient Kothduwa Temple island, and experiencing the famous 'fish therapy' spas right in the middle of the river.", latitude: 6.2719, longitude: 80.0544),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp92.jpg', place: "Meemure", rate: 4.8, description: "Traditional Village & Eco-Tourism Hub", category: "Nature", openingHours: "24/7 (Best experienced as a 2-3 day camping trip; roads are best navigated in daylight)", ticketPrice: "Free (Village tours, camping packages, and water activity guides range from LKR 3,000 - 8,000+)", fullDescription: "Tucked away deep inside the misty Knuckles Mountain Range, Meemure is one of Sri Lanka's most remote and beautifully preserved traditional villages. Dominated by the iconic pyramid-shaped Lakegala Rock, this eco-paradise features stunning terraced paddy fields, crystal-clear natural pools, and numerous waterfalls. It is a legendary spot for camping, trekking, and thrilling natural water slides, offering a complete escape from modern digital life.", latitude: 7.4333, longitude: 80.8383),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp93.jpg', place: "Ritigala Archaeological Site", rate: 4.7, description: "Mystical Ancient Monastery in a Forest Reserve", category: "Historical", openingHours: "8:00 AM - 5:00 PM", ticketPrice: "LKR 50 for locals, around LKR 1,000 - 1,500 for foreign visitors", fullDescription: "Ritigala is an ancient Buddhist monastery and mountain reserve dating back to the 1st century BCE. Nestled within a strict nature reserve, the site features remarkably preserved stone pathways, sunken courtyards, raised meditation platforms, and large stone baths used by ascetic monks (Pamsukulika). Shrouded in deep jungle foliage and myths from the Ramayana, the mountain range also possesses a distinct cooler microclimate harboring rare medicinal herbs found nowhere else in the dry zone plains.", latitude: 8.1147, longitude: 80.6586),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp94.jpg', place: "Madol Duwa", rate: 4.4, description: "Legendary Literary Island in Koggala Lake", category: "Nature", openingHours: "7:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best experienced via a morning boat safari)", ticketPrice: "Free to step onto the island (Boat rides from the Koggala lake banks range from LKR 2,500 - 4,500+ per boat)", fullDescription: "Madol Duwa is a small, enchanting island nestled within the expansive Koggala Lake in the southern province of Sri Lanka. Immortalized by the legendary Sri Lankan author Martin Wickramasinghe in his famous children's novel 'Madol Doova', this mangrove-shaded island brings the adventurous tales of Upali and Jinna to life. A scenic boat ride through the lake rewards visitors with quiet walking paths on the island, bird watching, and a nostalgic journey into local literature.", latitude: 5.9996, longitude: 80.3664),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp95.jpg', place: "Nalanda Gedige", rate: 4.6, description: "The Geographical Centre & Hybrid Stone Temple", category: "Historical", openingHours: "7:00 AM - 5:30 PM", ticketPrice: "Free (Donations appreciated)", fullDescription: "Nalanda Gedige is an ancient, enigmatic stone temple situated near Matale, built between the 8th and 10th centuries. It stands out as a unique architectural anomaly in Sri Lanka, displaying a distinct blend of Hindu Pallava-style architecture and traditional Buddhist elements, including subtle Tantric carvings. Originally located on a low-lying plain that faced flooding due to the Bowatenna Reservoir project, the entire monolithic structure was systematically dismantled and reconstructed on higher ground in the 1980s. Historically, it is also recognized as the exact geographical center of Sri Lanka.", latitude: 7.6683, longitude: 80.6453),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp96.jpg', place: "Pasikuda Beach", rate: 4.6, description: "Shallow Turquoise Waters & Luxury Bay", category: "Beaches", openingHours: "24/7 (Best for swimming and water sports: 6:00 AM - 6:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "Pasikuda Beach is an internationally acclaimed coastal resort bay located on the eastern coast of Sri Lanka, about 35 kilometers north of Batticaloa. Famous for its vibrant turquoise outer reef, it features one of the longest stretches of shallow coastline in the world, allowing visitors to walk hundreds of meters into the sea comfortably with waves barely reaching chest height. The calm, current-free bay makes it a premier destination for safe swimming, jet-skiing, windsurfing, and beachfront luxury relaxation.", latitude: 7.9226, longitude: 81.5644),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp97.jpg', place: "Royal Palace of King Parakramabahu", rate: 4.7, description: "Seven-Story Ancient Monolithic Palace Ruins", category: "Historical", openingHours: "7:00 AM - 6:00 PM", ticketPrice: "Included in the main Polonnaruwa Ancient City cultural triangle ticket (LKR 100 for locals, around \$30 USD for foreigners)", fullDescription: "The Royal Palace of King Parakramabahu I, historically named the Vaijayanta Prasada, is a magnificent structural marvel located in the ancient citadel of Polonnaruwa. Built during the 12th century, historical chronicles describe it as a massive seven-story palace supported by thick brick walls and wooden upper floors, containing over 1,000 rooms. Today, the impressive, towering remains of the main central building's brick walls, massive foundation stones, and the adjacent royal bathing pool (Kumara Pokuna) showcase the grandeur and advanced engineering of the Polonnaruwa Kingdom.", latitude: 7.9324, longitude: 81.0008),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp98.jpg', place: "Wilpattu National Park", rate: 4.6, description: "Sri Lanka's Largest National Park & Land of Lakes", category: "Nature", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best for safari: 6:00 AM - 10:00 AM or 3:00 PM - 6:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Local entry around LKR 150 - 300; Foreign entry around \$25 - \$30 USD (Excluding vehicle/service fees; safari jeep cost varies from LKR 8,000 - 15,000+)", fullDescription: "Spanning over 130,000 hectares across the North Western and North Central provinces, Wilpattu National Park is Sri Lanka's largest and one of its oldest protected reserves. The park is uniquely characterized by its 'Willus'—natural, rainwater-filled lakes surrounded by open white sand plains. Renowned globally for its leopard (Panthera pardus kotiya) and sloth bear populations, Wilpattu offers a deeply authentic, less crowded wilderness experience compared to other parks, cutting through dense dry-zone forests and rich historical terrain linked to early Sinhalese royalty.", latitude: 8.4354, longitude: 80.0078),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp99.jpg', place: "Sinharaja Forest Reserve", rate: 4.8, description: "UNESCO Rain Forest & Biodiversity Hotspot", category: "Nature", openingHours: "6:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best hiked in the morning; strictly accompanied by a guide)", ticketPrice: "Local entry around LKR 100 - 200; Foreign entry around \$15 - \$20 USD (Compulsory local guide fees vary from LKR 2,500 - 4,000+ depending on the trail)", fullDescription: "Sinharaja Forest Reserve is a world-renowned tropical lowland rain forest and a designated UNESCO World Heritage Site spanning across the Southern, Sabaragamuwa, and Western provinces. It serves as a critical biodiversity hotspot, home to over 60% of Sri Lanka's endemic trees and more than 50% of the island's endemic wildlife, including rare birds, amphibians, and butterflies. The forest is famous for its dense canopy, mystical misty pathways, stunning waterfalls, and the unique phenomenon of 'mixed-species bird flocks' that move together through the jungle.", latitude: 6.3889, longitude: 80.4578),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp100.jpg', place: "Yapahuwa Rock Fortress", rate: 4.7, description: "Ancient Ephemeral Capital", category: "Historical", openingHours: "7:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best to climb in the early morning or cooler evening hours)", ticketPrice: "LKR 100 for locals, around LKR 1,000 - 1,500 for foreign visitors", fullDescription: "Yapahuwa Rock Fortress is a magnificent historic citadel built upon a 90-meter-high monolithic rock near Maho in the Kurunegala district. Serving as the capital of Sri Lanka in the late 13th century under King Buvanekabahu I, it safely housed the Sacred Tooth Relic during turbulent times. The fortress is globally renowned for its masterpiece of ancient craftsmanship: a steeply rising, exquisitely carved stone staircase leading to the royal palace precinct. This staircase features intricate reliefs of dancers, musicians, and the legendary, highly stylized Yapahuwa Lions, reflecting a unique fusion of local and foreign artistic influences.", latitude: 7.8286, longitude: 80.3169),
  DestinationModel(coverImage: 'hp101.jpg', place: "Jaffna Fort", rate: 4.5, description: "Star-Shaped Dutch Rampart", category: "Historical", openingHours: "8:00 AM - 6:00 PM (Best for sunset walks: 4:30 PM - 6:00 PM)", ticketPrice: "Free", fullDescription: "Jaffna Fort is a massive colonial fortress situated on the southeastern edge of the Jaffna peninsula, overlooking the scenic lagoon. Originally built by the Portuguese in 1618, it was later captured, completely rebuilt, and expanded by the Dutch into a sophisticated, geometrically regular pentagonal stronghold fortified with a star-shaped moat. Steeped in centuries of colonial history and having survived heavy damage during the civil war, the beautifully restored limestone and coral walls stand today as a resilient monument of the north.", latitude: 9.6621, longitude: 80.0083),


